Animation: Building the Binomial Recursively

Joyce Robbins

3/5/2019

library(tidyverse)
library(gganimate)
make_df <- function(n) {
  heads <- tibble(
    x = 1:(n + 1),
    size = n + 1,
    prob = dbinom(0:n, n, .5) / 2,
    stage = n + .5,
    group = 1:(n + 1),
    fill = "p(x-1) n trials",
    column = "n"
  )
  
  tails <- tibble(
    x = 0:n,
    size = n + 1,
    prob = dbinom(0:n, n, .5) / 2,
    stage = n + .5,
    group = 1:(n + 1),
    fill = "p(x) n trials",
    column = "n"
  )
  
  all <- tibble(
    x = 0:n,
    size = n,
    prob = dbinom(0:n, n, .5),
    stage = n,
    group = 1:(n + 1),
    fill = "p(x) n+1 trials",
    column = "n + 1"
  )
  
  rbind(heads, tails, all) %>% 
    mutate(fill = fct_relevel(fill, "all", after = Inf))
  
}

num <- 10

df <- purrr::map_dfr(1:num, make_df)

If \(p=.5\), half of \(P(X=x) + (P = x-1)\) for \(n\) trials gives us \((P = x)\) for \(n+1\) trials. (For a more thorough explanation on why this is true, see Understandng the Binomial Recursively.)

That is,

\[\frac{b(x; n, .5)}{2} + \frac{b(x-1; n, .5)}{2} = b(x; n+1, .5)\]

This animation demonstrates this recursion visually for \(n = 2\) to \(n = 10\): the red and blue represent half of the probabilities for \(n\) trials, while the purple bars represent the binomial probabilities for \(n+1\) trials. (Note that the blue bars are half the height of the purple barsthe \(x's\) are the same so the purple bars shrink into the blue ones for \(n+1\) trials.)

g <-
  ggplot(df, aes(x, prob, fill = fill, group = group)) +
  geom_col() + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "blue", "purple"))

anim <- 
  g + transition_states(stage) + exit_recolor(fill = "purple")

animate(anim, fps = 5)

Animations can be hard to digest, so heres a static version:

df %>% filter(size != 1, size != max(size)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x, prob, fill = fill)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "blue", "purple")) +
  facet_grid(size ~ column)
